        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "An "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnbillboardconstraint"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object automatically adjusts a node’s orientation so that its local z-axis always points toward the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnscenerenderer/1523982-pointofview"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " node currently being used to render the scene. For example, you can use a billboard constraint to efficiently render parts of a scene using two-dimensional sprite images instead of three-dimensional geometry—by mapping sprites onto planes affected by a billboard constraint, the sprites maintain their orientation with respect to the viewer. To attach constraints to an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object, use its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode/1408016-constraints"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
